This course in an introduction to philosophy through an examination of some philosophical problems such as the nature and existence of God, freedom and determinism, the nature of mind, and ethical theory. Students will read both historical and contemporary texts.&#8232;
&#8232;The majority of students found this course interesting and fascinating. A couple of students said it was a “great introductory course to philosophy,” and “painless and fun.” Though, one student did comment that overall this was a poor class.&#8232;&#8232;
Students found Professor Riley to be able to convey the material without making it hard to understand. Another student described Professor Riley and his wife as “extremely knowledgeable, passionate, funny, and charismatic.” However, one student did mention that, “Professor Gresham Riley did not convey the context of the class very well.” One student also mentioned that Professor Pamela Riley was a wonderful addition to the course “not only because of the unique insights she brings to the class through her interactions with us and Gresham, but most of all because she's added a whole other dimension to the course through her vast expertise in literature and drama.” &#8232;&#8232;
One student mentioned that “there was a significant amount of work required,” and another mentioned that it was “intellectually rigorous.” Several students commented that they would recommend this to anyone. This course fulfills the Humanities & Social Science Sector. Freshman Seminar sections are offered.
